metadata.name: Letter #100
metadata.description:
This is a letter from the computer to you by asemic writing. Imagine what message is written on it.

The artwork is inspired from Shodo(書道) that is known as Japanese calligraphy.
Shodo is the way of writing Kanji and Kana characters with a brush in India ink.
It's one of the traditional Japanese arts.

Paper Color and Ink Color combinations has 18 variations.
Aspect Ratio has 5 variations.
Font Size has 3 variations.
Font Weight has 3 variations.
Font Style has 3 variations.
Each character is randomly generated by a mathematical algorithm.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [f] to switch full screen on and off
- Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
- Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 4800 pixel  (wait a minutes)

Create with p5.js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.description:
Grud, a speedrun on 31st May 2022. 

The cousin of the BoodMoards, exploring some other shapes, colours and fun ideas.

10 background colours

Big thanks to all collectors and shoutout to the Circolors frens for the support <3 

10% of mint proceeds going to the processing foundation 
42% of royalties to minters.

metadata.name: Gardens of delusion #43
metadata.description:
We live in a perpetual state of assertive belief, and the outside world never faults us, because we escape contradiction through a process of delusion. How reassuring it is to wander in the alleys of subjectivity and take a seat to look at these gardens we create.

Click to play the audio track.
You can zoom in/out, drag and pan.
Press « A » to toggle the autoplay mode that will change the scene every 600 frames.
Press the space bar to download a screenshot of the current frame :
- width : 4096px
- height : based on ratio
- file format : PNG

metadata.name: Square Planets #228
metadata.description:
Square Planets was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Planetary Folklore Participations No. 2. (c. 1970). Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the third in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

Square Planets consists of four layers of squares contained within a background square superimposed on top of one another. Each layer is translated from the previous layer but still lies within its boundaries. The background color of each layer is random and its set of squares are another random color. The squares that make up layers two and three are rotated either clockwise or counter-clockwise some random number of degrees within a predetermined range. 

There are many Gestalt interactions within this piece. Layers (square planets) interact with each other in interesting ways. Each new generation with its random color assignments significantly affect your depth perception. Layers appear to come forward or recede. Sometimes there is more "after-imagism" between the square sets. Candy for your mind.
